do, Boulder]]\n|religion     = [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod|Lutheranism]]\n}}\n'''Cory Scott Gardner'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legistorm.com/memberbio/2735/Rep_Cory_Gardner_CO.html |title=Representative Cory Scott Gardner (Cory) (R-Colorado, 4th) - Biography from |publisher=LegiStorm |date= |accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref> (born August 22, 1974) is an American politician who is the [[United States Senate|United States Senator-elect]] from [[Colorado]]. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he is currently a member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Colorado's 4th congressional district]]. Prior to that, he was a member of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]].\n\nGardner announced his candidacy for the U.S. Senate in March 2014, quickly clearing the Republican primary field,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/201036-gardners-final-primary-foe-drops-bid-in-colorado/|title=Gardner gets clear primary path in Colorado|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=18 March 2014}}</ref> and defeated Democratic incumbent [[Mark Udall]] in the [[United States Senate election in Colorado, 2014|November 2014 race]].<ref name=\"abc.results\">{{Cite news|url = http://abc30.com/news/republicans-up-5-seats-in-race-to-control-senate/380215/|title = REPUBLICANS UP 5 SEATS IN RACE TO CONTROL SENATE|last = |first = |date = |work = |accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\n\nGardner was born on August 22, 1974 in [[Yuma, Colorado]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Cory Gardner's Political Summary|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/30004/cory-gardner#.VAjni0h8Gnc|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> the son of Cindy L. (n\u00e9e Pagel) and John W. Gardner. His ancestry includes Irish, German, Austrian, and English.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/gardner.htm |title=Cory Gardner ancestry |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> He graduated [[summa cum laude]] from [[Colorado State University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] in 1997.<ref name=\"NatlJGardner\">[http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2014-new-members/colorado-senate-cory-gardner-r-20141104 Colorado Senate: Cory Gardner (R)], ''[[National Journal]]''.</ref> In college, Gardner switched from the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] to the Republican Party<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Sara |date=October 17, 2014 |title=GOP Senate Candidate Puts Colorado Democrats Off Balance |url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/gop-senate-candidate-puts-colorado-democrats-off-balance-1413587405 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |location=[[New York City|New York]] |accessdate=October 18, 2014 |quote=He entered Colorado State University as a Democrat and switched to the Republican Party in college.}}</ref> and interned at the [[Colorado State Capitol]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kosena|first1=Jason|title=Cory Gardner joins Tom Lucero in GOP bid against Betsy Markey|url=http://www.coloradostatesman.com/content/991020-cory-gardner-joins-tom-lucero-gop-bid-against-betsy-markey|accessdate=4 September 2014|publisher=Colorado Statesman|date=2009-05-15}}</ref>  He also studied abroad for a semester in [[Bremen, Germany]], and is fluent in German.<ref>\"Profiles, The Rocky Mountain Collegian, 11 June 1995</ref> He went to law school at the [[University of Colorado School of Law|University of Colorado]] to earn his [[Juris Doctor]] in 2001.<ref name=\"NatlJGardner\"/> Gardner served as [[General Counsel]] and Legislative Director for former U.S. Senator [[Wayne Allard]] of Colorado from 2002 to 2005.<ref name=\"NatlJGardner\"/><ref name=wsj>{{cite web|title=Cory Gardner (R)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/cory-gardner--CO-H|website=Election 2012|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Colorado House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nGardner was appointed to the Colorado House of Representatives in 2005 and elected to a full term in 2006. He represented District 63 in the Colorado House of Representatives from 2005 through 2011.<ref name=wsj/>\n\n===Tenure===\nHe proposed legislation in 2006 that would set aside money in a rainy-day fund that would help protect the state from future economic downturns. His proposal relied on Referendum C money{{what|date=October 2014}} for future budget emergencies.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DP&p_theme=dp&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10F65265527762F0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |author=Couch, Mark P. | title=Rainy day funding bills see daylight | work=Denver Post | date=January 26, 2006 | accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> He staunchly opposed any tax increases. He helped create the Colorado Clean Energy Development Authority, which issued bonds to finance projects that involve the production, transportation and storage of clean energy until it was repealed in 2012.<ref name=DOE>{{cite web|title=Clean Energy Development Authority|url=http://www.afdc.energy.gov/laws/law/CO/6291|publisher=United States Department of Energy|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gardner.house.gov/about-me/biography |title=Biography &#124; Congressman Cory Gardner |publisher=Gardner.house.gov |date= |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, he called on Republican Governor [[Bill Owens (Colorado politician)|Bill Owens]] to call a special session addressing the issue of [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SJAB&p_theme=sjab&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1123D1069CD55518&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=Court ruling riles solons |work=Journal-Advocate |date=June 13, 2006 |author=Mangalonzo, John |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Gardner opposed legislation to allow pharmacists to prescribe emergency contraception,<ref name=\"Marcotte\">{{cite web|last1=Marcotte|first1=Amanda|title=Why Is This Anti-Contraception Republican in Favor of Over-the-Counter Birth Control Pills?|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2014/06/23/cory_gardner_on_contraception_colorado_senate_candidate_supports_over_the.html|publisher=Slate|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> and offered an amendment to the budget to prohibit the state Medicaid plan from purchasing [[Emergency contraception#Plan B|Plan B emergency contraception]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Couch|first1=Mark P.|title=LEGISLATURE 2006 House gives OK to budget|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DP&p_theme=dp&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=Cory%20Gardner%20AND%20date%2803/31/2006%20to%2003/31/2006%29&p_field_date-0=YMD_date&p_params_date-0=date:B,E&p_text_date-0=03/31/2006%20to%2003/31/2006%29&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=%28%22Cory%20Gardner%22%29&xcal_numdocs=50&p_perpage=25&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no|publisher=The Denver Post|accessdate=13 July 2014|date=31 March 2006}}</ref> In 2007, Gardner voted against a bill requiring hospitals to inform survivors of a sexual assault of the availability of emergency contraception.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gardner, under fire on personhood, suggests making birth control available over the counter|url=http://kdvr.com/2014/06/19/planned-parenthood-joins-chorus-attacking-gardner-on-personhood/|publisher=Fox 31 Denver|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1F793DB59E15039A87257251007C3BA1?Open&file=060_enr.pdf|title=Senate Bill 07-690|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Denver Post]]'' hailed Gardner as \u201cthe GOP Idea Man\u201d. He was named one of the Top 40 young Republican lawmakers by the magazine ''Rising Tide''. He became House Minority Whip in January 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=355746 |title=United States > Colorado > CO State House > Minority Whip |publisher=www.ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*House Education Committee<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated |first=The |url=http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20070330/NEWS/70330010 |title=GOP calls for House education chairman to step down over e-mail |publisher=SummitDaily.com |date=2007-03-30 |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=CSGB&d_place=CSGB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=116DF41746FC3D10&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=NewsLibrary.com - newspaper archive, clipping service - newspapers and other news sources |publisher=Nl.newsbank.com |date=2007-01-23 |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n*House Agriculture and Natural Resources Committee\n*Legislative Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/Cory_Gardner |title=Cory Gardner |publisher=Ballotpedia |date= |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2010#District 4}}\nGardner won the Republican primary in the 4th Congressional District to challenge Democratic incumbent [[Betsy Markey]]. Also running were American Constitution Party nominee Doug Aden and Independent Ken \"Wasko\" Waszkiewicz. In an early September poll, Gardner was up 50% to 39% over Markey.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nationalreview.com/battle10/245491/gardner-leads-markey-50-39-first-public-co-4-poll-michael-sandoval# |author=Sandoval, Michael |title=Gardner Leads Markey 50-39 in First Public CO-4 Poll | work=National Review |date=September 2, 2010 |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nGardner was named one of the GOP Young Guns. He was endorsed by former U.S. Congressman [[Tom Tancredo]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/29/tom-tancredo-standing-by-_n_698316.html | title=Tom Tancredo Standing By Endorsement Of Cory Gardner Over ACP Candidate In CD-4 | work=Huffington Post Denver | date=29 October 2010 |accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> On November 2, 2010, Gardner defeated Markey, 52%-41%.\n \n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2012#District 4}}\nGardner ran unopposed in the Republican primary before going on to defeat Democratic nominee [[Brandon Shaffer]] 59%-37% in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|title=OFFICIAL RESULTS|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/43032/116650/en/summary.html|website=Colorado Election Results|publisher=Colorado Secretary of State|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n===Tenure===\n====Energy and environmental issues====\nShortly after taking office, Gardner introduced legislation that would speed up clean-air permits for companies engaged in offshore drilling in Alaska, which he says would create jobs and reduce dependence on foreign oil.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/morning_call/2011/06/house-passes-gardner-bill-on-offshore.html | title=House passes Gardner bill on offshore drilling | newspaper=Denver Business Journal | date=23 June 2011 |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> The House passed Gardner's bill  by a vote of 253 to 166 on June 22, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rep. Gardner's Jobs and Permitting Act Passes House |date=22 June 2011 |url=http://gardner.house.gov/press-release/rep-gardner%E2%80%99s-jobs-and-permitting-act-passes-house |accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2013, Gardner introduced the [[Reducing Excessive Deadline Obligations Act of 2013 (H.R. 2279; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would amend the [[Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act of 1980]] and the [[Solid Waste Disposal Act]].<ref name=2279sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2279 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th/house-bill/2279|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> It is bill that would change the frequency of reports from the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) about solid waste regulations.<ref name=billboosts>{{cite news|last=Hattem|first=Julian|title=Bills boosting states' environmental oversight pass first hurdle|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/e2-wire/303959-bills-boosting-states-environmental-oversight-pass-first-hurdle|accessdate=7 January 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> Instead of being forced to automatically review the regulations every three years, the EPA would be able to review them on an as needed basis.<ref name=housestart2014>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House to start 2014 with bill curbing EPA|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/194190-house-to-start-2014-with-bill-reining-in-epa|accessdate=7 January 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=31 December 2013}}</ref> It would also grant precedence to state financial requirements for hazardous substances over federal requirements.<ref name=\"billboosts\"/>\n\nOn March 6, 2014, Gardner introduced the [[Domestic Prosperity and Global Freedom Act (H.R. 6; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Energy]] (DOE) to issue a decision on an application for authorization to export [[natural gas]] within 90 days after the later of: (1) the end of the comment period for that decision as set forth in the [[Federal Register]], or (2) the date of enactment of this Act.<ref name=hr6sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 6 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/6|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nGardner has stated that he believes [[climate change]] is occurring, but he is unsure whether humans are causing it.<ref>{{cite web|title=GOP civil war: A coup in Colorado|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/03/colorado-elections-2014-cory-gardner-mark-udall-105082.html?hp=t2_3|publisher=Politico|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=Dylan|title=GOP Climate Change Skeptic Touts Wind Farm Support In Colorado|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/dc/cory-gardner-wind-farm-ad|accessdate=4 September 2014|publisher=Talking Points Memo|date=4 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Rick|title=Senate candidate Cory Gardner stumps in Aspen|url=http://www.postindependent.com/news/12688644-113/udall-gardner-sen-aspen|accessdate=4 September 2014|publisher=The Aspen Times|date=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\nGardner supports construction of the [[Keystone Pipeline]]. He is pro-[[fracking]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Restuccia|first1=Andrew|title=Keystone and the Udall-Gardner race|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/05/colorado-energys-continental-divide-106541.html|accessdate=5 September 2014|publisher=Politico|date=2014-05-12}}</ref>\n\n====Economic issues====\nIn March 2011, Gardner introduced bipartisan legislation that would require congressional committees to hold hearings on programs that are deemed duplicative by a U.S. Government Accountability Office report. Gardner has said he believes such a measure would reduce waste in government.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sherry|first=Allison|title=Beltway Breakfast \u2013Gardner tackles duplication, so does Udall, Bennet talks Race to the Top, GOP applauds themselves for cutting another $4 billion|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2011/03/02/beltway-breakfast-gardner-tackles-duplication-so-does-udall-bennet-talks-race-to-the-top-gop-applauds-themselves-for-cutting-another-4-billion/24327/|work=The Spot|publisher=The Denver Post|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://gardner.house.gov/press-release/rep-gardner-announces-resolution-tackle-duplicative-programs-and-govt-waste |title=Rep. Gardner Announces Resolution to Tackle Duplicative Programs and Govt. Waste | accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nGardner voted for the [[Paul Ryan Budget|Ryan budget plan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/112/house/1/277 |title=House Vote 277 - Passes Ryan Budget Bill |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=Dems target House GOP Senate hopefuls after Ryan vote|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/203217-dems-target-house-gop-senate-hopefuls-after-ryan-vote|accessdate=5 September 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=2014-04-10}}</ref>\n\nGardner is a signer of [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge|Americans for Tax Reform]]\u2019s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name=\"ATR\">{{cite web |title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List |url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf |publisher=Americans for Tax Reform |accessdate=30 November 2011}}</ref> He also strongly supports legislation which would require that the [[US Federal Reserve]] be audited.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/10/us-usa-fed-politics-idUSKBN0FF0C420140710 | title=Fed independence questioned as Republicans ramp up pressure | publisher=Reuters | date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 2014, Gardner introduced legislation to reform the [[Earned Income Tax Credit]] program.  The legislation seeks to reduce fraud in the program and dedicate the savings to increasing the credit for working families.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gardner Bill Would Improve EITC Program |url=http://krai.com/gardner-bill-improve-eitc-program/#more-21324 |publisher=KRAI |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Gardner broke ranks with the Republican Party and voted against a bill that would have dismantled the [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foley|first1=Elise|title=House Votes To Strip Deportation Relief From Dreamers|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/01/house-bill-daca_n_5643287.html|accessdate=4 September 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=1 August 2014}}</ref> Gardner says he supports immigration reform in the form of a guest worker program and increased border security.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegler|first1=Kirk|title=Colo. Democrats Bet On Immigration To Boost Udall's Re-Election Bid|url=http://www.npr.org/2014/08/28/343900791/colo-democrats-bet-on-immigration-to-boost-udalls-re-election-bid|accessdate=4 September 2014|publisher=NPR|date=2014-08-28}}</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nIn 2011, he voted in support of the \u201cRespect for Rights of Conscience Act\u201d, which states that \u201cnothing in the Affordable Care Act shall be construed to authorize a health plan to require a provider to provide, participate in, or refer for a specific item or service contrary to the provider\u2019s religious beliefs or moral convictions.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=Gardner, under fire on personhood, suggests making birth control available over the counter|url=http://kdvr.com/2014/06/19/planned-parenthood-joins-chorus-attacking-gardner-on-personhood/|publisher=Fox 31 Denver|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2013, Gardner announced that he would introduce a bill to prohibit executives of [[healthcare exchange|state healthcare exchanges]] from getting bonuses. According to ''Ripon Advance'', a CEO of a state health exchange with low enrollment got a bonus, and Gardner's bill would seek to prevent that from happening.<ref>Martin, Aaron. [http://riponadvance.com/news/gardner-bill-curb-aca-compensation/5840 \"Gardner bill would curb ACA compensation]\". ''Ripon Advance''. 2013-12-09 (Retrieved 2014-02-14).</ref>\n\n====Social issues====\nIn 2012, Gardner was one of 33 Republicans to vote for the Senate version of the [[Violence Against Women Act|Violence Against Women Act of 1994 (VAWA)]], which re-authorized the bill and expanded protections for Native Americans, immigrants, and gays.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bartels |first1=Lynn |title=Rep. Cory Gardner is praised by Planned Parenthood? |url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2014/03/28/cory-gardner-plannedparenthood/107325/ |publisher=The Denver Post |accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 and 2013, Gardner co-sponsored [[personhood]] legislation titled the \"Life Begins at Conception Act\".<ref name=politico_personhood>{{cite web|title=Cory Gardner changes stance on personhood|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/03/cory-gardner-personhood-colorado-senate-election-2014-104963.html|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>\nGardner later said that he changed his mind on personhood, after listening to voters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Udall hits Gardner on personhood; Gardner, GOP hit back at \u2018divisive\u2019 attacks|url=http://kdvr.com/2014/06/17/gop-preempts-new-udall-tv-ad-attacking-gardner-on-personhood/|publisher=Fox 31 Denver|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> According to ''The Denver Post'', \u201cGardner conceded that with his new position on personhood, he might be accused of flip-flopping simply to make himself more palatable to statewide voters.\u201d<ref name=denverpost_personhood>{{cite web|last1=Bartels|first1=Lynn|title=Cory Gardner changes position on personhood issue|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_25395470/senate-bombshell-cory-gardner-says-cant-support-personhood|publisher=The Denver Post|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The nonpartisan Factcheck.org said \u201cIt would be clearer to say that Gardner supports efforts to ban abortion that could also ban some forms of birth control. As for his change of position, voters in Colorado should know Gardner still supports a federal bill that would prompt the same concerns over birth control as the state measure he says he rejects on the same grounds.\u201d<ref>Factcheck.org. August 15, 2014. [http://www.factcheck.org/2014/08/a-fight-over-birth-control-in-colorado/]. ''Factcheck.org'' Retrieved: 27 October 2014.</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Gardner called for [[Over-the-counter drug|over-the-counter]] access to [[Oral contraceptive pill|oral contraceptives]] and  said the birth control pill would be safer and cheaper if it was available over the counter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Cory|title=Cory Gardner: Women should be able to buy the pill without a prescription|url=http://www.denverpost.com/opinion/ci_25995739/women-should-be-able-buy-pill-without-prescription|accessdate=11 July 2014|publisher=Denver Post|date=2014-06-19}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the October 2014 announcement from the U.S. Supreme Court allowing [[same-sex marriage]] to become the law in 30 states including Colorado, Gardner reaffirmed his position that marriage should only be between a man and a woman but stated, \"This issue is in the hands of the courts and we must honor their legal decisions.\"<ref>Stokols, Eli. October 7, 2014. [http://kdvr.com/2014/10/07/gardner-my-views-on-marriage-have-long-been-clear/ Gardner: \u2018My views on marriage have long been clear\u2019]. ''FOX 31 Denver.'' Retrieved: 7 October 2014.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n*[[Republican Study Committee]]\n\n==2014 Senate election==\n{{main|United States Senate election in Colorado, 2014}}\nGardner was the Republican nominee for Senate, and won against incumbent Senator Mark Udall in the general election. Gardner won by a 3% margin over Udall, with a 49% to 46% advantage. Gardner had received 965,974 votes overcoming Udall's 916,245 votes.  <ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Kurtis|title=Rep. Cory Gardner wins big at assembly, will challenge Sen. Mark Udall|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_25553402/u-s-rep-cory-gardner-clear-favorite-become|accessdate=28 October 2014|publisher=Denver Post|date=Apr 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"abc.results\" />\n\nIn October 2014, the ''Denver Post'' endorsed Gardner, writing that \"he has emphasized economic and energy issues (and was, for example, an early supporter among Republicans of renewable energy). ... \"his past views on same-sex marriage are becoming irrelevant now that the Supreme Court has let appeals court rulings stand and marriage equality appears unstoppable. And contrary to Udall's tedious refrain, Gardner's election would pose no threat to abortion rights.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Cory Gardner for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_26701817/cory-gardner-u-s-senate|accessdate=28 October 2014|publisher=Denver Post|date=Oct 10, 2014}}</ref> Former [[Denver Broncos]] quarterback [[John Elway]] endorsed Gardner.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Richardson|first1=Valerie|title=NFL politics: Elway backs Gardner in Colorado as progressives target Denver Broncos fans|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/oct/23/elway-backs-gardner-progressives-aim-broncos-fans/|accessdate=28 October 2014|publisher=Washington Times|date=Oct 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[No Labels]] performed independent get-out-the-vote efforts on behalf of its Problem Solvers, including Gardner.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogers|first1=Alex|title=How Joe Manchin Ended Up Getting Out the Vote Against a Fellow Democrat|url=http://time.com/3542074/joe-manchin-no-labels-cory-gardner-mark-udall-colorado/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+time%2Ftopstories+TIME%3A+Top+Stories|accessdate=28 October 2014|publisher=Time|date=Oct 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=Colorado District 63 election, 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=302126 |title=CO State House District 63 Race - Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (US)\n|candidate=Cory Gardner|votes=15,736|percentage=73.3%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|candidate=Pauline Artery|votes=5,732|percentage=26.7%|change=}}{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title=Colorado District 63 election, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=464175 |title=CO State House 063 Race - Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (US)\n|candidate=Cory Gardner|votes=|percentage=100.0|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gardner.house.gov/ Congressman Cory Gardner] official U.S. House site\n*[http://corygardner.com/ Cory Gardner for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Colorado/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Cory_Gardner_%5BR-4%5D|Cory Gardner}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = G000562 | ballot = Cory_Gardner | nndb = 871/000264079 | votesmart = 30004 | govtrack = 412406 | opencong = 412406 | rollcall = 32149 | politifact = | fec = H0CO04122 | opensecrets = N00030780 | assets = cory-gardner | legistorm = 2735/Rep_Cory_Gardner_CO.html | followthemoney = 4498 | ontheissues = House/Cory_Gardner.htm | congress = cory-gardner/1998 | worldcat = | c-span = corygardner | imdb = 5566347 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAAaFWKP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betsy Markey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Colorado|U.S. House of Representatives]]